Plot Raster Data

  • Break up continuous data
  • Use custom break values
  • Enhance plot with terrain colors

This episode covers how to plot a raster in R using the ggplot2 package with customized coloring schemes. It also covers how to layer a raster on top of a hillshade to produce an eloquent map. We will continue working with the Digital Surface Model (DSM) raster for the NEON Harvard Forest Field Site.

Objectives

  • Build customized plots for a single band raster using the ggplot2 package.
  • Layer a raster dataset on top of a hillshade to create an elegant basemap.

keypoints

  • Continuous data ranges can be grouped into categories using mutate() and cut().
  • Use built-in terrain.colors() or set your preferred color scheme manually.

If youre just opening up this project, youll have to load the packages and data used in previous episodes.

# load packages 
library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)


# data loaded from earlier episode
# DSM data for Harvard Forest
dtm <- raster("data/raster/HARV_dtmCrop.tif")
dtm_df <- as.data.frame(dtm, xy = TRUE)

Break up continuous data

In the previous episode, we viewed our data using a continuous color ramp. For clarity and visibility of the plot, we may prefer to view the data symbolized or colored according to ranges of values. This is comparable to a classified map. To do this, we need to tell ggplot how many groups to break our data into, and where those breaks should be. To make these decisions, it is useful to first explore the distribution of the data using a bar plot. To begin with, we will use dplyrs mutate() function combined with cut() to split the data into 3 bins.

# add column of binned elevation to df using mutate
# new column should break values into 3 bins using the cut function
dtm_df <- dtm_df %>%
                mutate(bin_elevation = cut(HARV_dtmCrop, breaks = 3))

# plot binned elevation with a bar chart
ggplot() +
    geom_bar(data = dtm_df, aes(bin_elevation))

Use custom break values

We might prefer to customize the cutoff values for these groups. Lets round the cutoff values so that we have groups for the ranges of 301350 m, 351400 m, and 401450 m. To implement this we will give mutate() a numeric vector of break points instead of the number of breaks we want.

# create vector of bins values
custom_bins <- c(300, 325, 350, 375,400)

# use custom bins in cut function
dtm_df <- dtm_df %>%
  mutate(bin3_elevation = cut(HARV_dtmCrop, breaks = custom_bins))

# look at bin values
unique(dtm_df$bin3_elevation)
## [1] (350,375] (325,350] (375,400]
## Levels: (300,325] (325,350] (350,375] (375,400]

And now we can plot our bar plot again, using the new groups:

# bar chart using custom bins
ggplot() +
  geom_bar(data = dtm_df, aes(bin3_elevation))

We can use those groups to plot our raster data, with each group being a different color:

ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = dtm_df , aes(x = x, y = y, fill = bin3_elevation)) + 
  coord_quickmap()

Enhance plot with terrain colors

The plot above uses the default colors inside ggplot for raster objects. We can specify our own colors to make the plot look a little nicer. R has a built in set of colors for plotting terrain, which are built in to the terrain.colors() function. Since we have three bins, we want to create a 3-color palette:

# look at hex codes for colors
terrain.colors(3)
## [1] "#00A600" "#ECB176" "#F2F2F2"

The terrain.colors() function returns hex colors - each of these character strings represents a color. To use these in our map, we pass them across using the scale_fill_manual() function.

# plor binned elevation using terrain colors
ggplot() +
 geom_raster(data = dtm_df , aes(x = x, y = y,
                                      fill = bin3_elevation)) + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = terrain.colors(3)) + 
    coord_quickmap()

We can continue to enhance this plot by adding more bins or classes of elevation data and adding other plot elements, such as a title and axis labels. Lets break up the elevation data into 6 classes and add some helpful plot elements.

dtm_df <- dtm_df  %>%
               mutate(bin6_elevation = cut(HARV_dtmCrop, breaks = 6)) 

# plot
ggplot() +
    geom_raster(data = dtm_df , aes(x = x, y = y,
                                      fill = bin6_elevation)) + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = terrain.colors(6), name = "Elevation") + 
    ggtitle("Classified Elevation Map - NEON Harvard Forest Field Site") +
    xlab("UTM Easting Coordinate (m)") +
    ylab("UTM Northing Coordinate (m)") + 
    coord_quickmap()
